label("$D$",(0.7,-0.5),SE);
[/asy] We can see that the segments $AB$ and $CD$ intersect if and only if $A$ and $B$ are on the same side of the line $CD$ and $C$ and $D$ are on the same side of the line $AB$. This is because if $A$ and $B$ are on opposite sides of the line $CD$, then the segments $AB$ and $CD$ do not intersect. So, we can draw the line $CD$ and divide the circle into four sectors with equal arc lengths. Each sector has $1/4$ of the total circumference. If we draw a line through $A$ and $B$, then we will have to choose a point $P$ on the circle, so that $AP$ and $BP$ are of equal arc length. We can see that this is possible only if $A$, $B$, and $P$ are on the same side of the line $CD$. So, we have two possibilities: 1) $A$, $B$, $C$, and $D$ are on the same side of the line $CD$, or 2) $A$, $B$, $C$, and $D$ are on the opposite sides of the line $CD$. If $A$, $B$, $C$, and $D$ are on the same side of the line $CD$, then we can choose any one of the four points as $P$ (there are 4 ways to do this). If $A$, $B$, $C$, and $D$ are on the opposite sides of the line $CD$, then we can choose any one of the three remaining points as $P$ (there are 3 ways to do this). So, the probability is $\frac{4+3}{4}=\boxed{\frac{7}{4}}$.ครั้งแรก
